    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Sorry, Wrong Number</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>James Hyatt letter says William Safire is right to worry about inappropriate requests for Social Security numbers (May 11 column)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Defend Your Identity'' (column, May 11):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Defend Your Identity'' (column, May 11):</p>
        <p>William Safire is quite right to worry about inappropriate requests for Social Security numbers. A new video store chain in my hometown requests a Social Security number to open a video rental account. When confronted with such demands, I usually tell the clerk, ''Sure, so long as you give me your number.''</p>
        <p>The clerk doesn't, and I walk away.</p>
        <p>JAMES HYATT  Princeton, N.J., May 11, 2000</p>
      </block>
